I have a Kindle.

865
00:59:52,160 --> 00:59:55,280
I got all the things, but a physical book on the couch is the best.

866
00:59:55,280 --> 00:59:55,520
>> Yeah.

867
00:59:55,520 --> 00:59:59,839
It's just the nightlight is key cuz some you know at night time it's like >> you need a light.

868
00:59:59,839 --> 01:00:01,040
Okay.

869
01:00:01,040 --> 01:00:09,040
So, we've been talking mostly right so far about kind of individual improvement, how to figure out what you should be working on,

870
01:00:09,040 --> 01:00:12,559
just uh helping co learning to coach, things like that.

871
01:00:12,559 --> 01:00:20,880
I want to kind of take us up a little a level above and talk about team skills, help people get better at working with other people.

872
01:00:20,880 --> 01:00:26,559
Something that you're uh in many ways known for is helping co-founders build better relationships.

873
01:00:26,559 --> 01:00:31,520
And in my experience, this is one of the most challenging parts of starting a company is the co-founder relationship.

874
01:00:31,520 --> 01:00:33,520
You A lot of people don't realize what they're getting into.

875
01:00:33,520 --> 01:00:38,480
You're basically getting married to this person in like a very high stress situation and you sometimes don't know much about them.

876
01:00:38,480 --> 01:00:39,359
>> Exactly.

877
01:00:39,359 --> 01:00:49,200
>> And then you not working well together is just a huge issue because that all trickles down and everyone sees it and >> and you know when co-founders leave it's really bad for everyone.

878
01:00:49,200 --> 01:00:50,559
So let me just ask you this.

879
01:00:50,559 --> 01:00:55,920
What have you found most helpful in helping co-founders build great relationships, stay happy and productive?

880
01:00:55,920 --> 01:00:57,839
Yeah, thanks for asking this.

881
01:00:57,839 --> 01:01:06,799
I love working with co-founders because I think your core values as a person come out when they interact with someone else's core values.

882
01:01:06,799 --> 01:01:12,079
Conflict, healthy conflict or otherwise, is actually where your core values come out.

883
01:01:12,079 --> 01:01:19,680
So, it's fascinating to watch people try to do something incredibly hard in the context of someone else's vision,

884
01:01:19,680 --> 01:01:23,440
someone else's strengths and weaknesses, and navigate that together.

885
01:01:23,440 --> 01:01:28,480
So, there's so much energy in the co-founder dynamic for me and for co-founders themselves.

886
01:01:28,480 --> 01:01:35,440
It's actually something that people don't feel comfortable going to their board about or talking to that many people about because it's a private matter.

887
01:01:35,440 --> 01:01:41,760
It's almost like in a marriage, you go see a couple's therapist, but you don't tell all your friends that you can't stand your partner,

888
01:01:41,760 --> 01:01:43,359
but it keeps you up at night.

889
01:01:43,359 --> 01:01:49,359
So, it's a really tender, important relationship, and there aren't enough supports for co-founders to navigate it.

890
01:01:49,359 --> 01:01:50,880
It's very normal.

891
01:01:50,880 --> 01:01:53,359
In fact, I know you probably know this stat.

892
01:01:53,359 --> 01:01:57,760
65% of startups fail because of co-founder conflict.

893
01:01:57,760 --> 01:02:05,839
And co-founders are in a moment where they're trying to build the future for their business,

894
01:02:05,839 --> 01:02:07,760
but also trying to build their own livelihood.

895
01:02:07,760 --> 01:02:11,599
So, there's so much at stake to get along with your co-founder.

896
01:02:11,599 --> 01:02:19,359
And I think the the core at its core, what you need in a healthy relationship is one self-awareness.

897
01:02:19,359 --> 01:02:21,760
What do I bring into this dynamic?

898
01:02:21,760 --> 01:02:25,520
And how am I being experienced by the other person?

899
01:02:25,520 --> 01:02:28,799
What does this other person bring into the dynamic?

900
01:02:28,799 --> 01:02:31,920
And how am I reacting to that?

901
01:02:31,920 --> 01:02:36,799
So the first is just collective awareness about what is our dynamic.

902
01:02:36,799 --> 01:02:38,559
I like to use the enog for this.

903
01:02:38,559 --> 01:02:46,240
Um but there's all kinds of tools, self-awareness tools that you can use to give a common language to what is my thing and what is your thing.

904
01:02:46,240 --> 01:02:50,319
A very classic one has to do with roles.

905
01:02:50,319 --> 01:02:52,880
CTOs tend to be skeptics.

906
01:02:52,880 --> 01:02:54,960
They're they love facts.

907
01:02:54,960 --> 01:02:56,480
They seek knowledge.

908
01:02:56,480 --> 01:02:59,119
They want depth of awareness and understanding.

909
01:02:59,119 --> 01:03:02,160
And they also like to be self-sufficient.

910
01:03:02,160 --> 01:03:06,640
This is a total generalization, but I've seen this pattern over and over again.

911
01:03:06,640 --> 01:03:10,160
The CEO is the person who had to sell the vision.

912
01:03:10,160 --> 01:03:12,960
They're a person who loves big picture vision strategy.

913
01:03:12,960 --> 01:03:15,359
They often are great at influencing others.

914
01:03:15,359 --> 01:03:20,400
They love to sell ahead of the the reality of what the company's actually built.

915
01:03:20,400 --> 01:03:25,200
This creates an inherent tension between blind optimism and skepticism.

916
01:03:25,200 --> 01:03:28,799
And it's a dance that these two roles play together.

917
01:03:28,799 --> 01:03:30,960
So the first part is knowing the dance you're in.

918
01:03:30,960 --> 01:03:34,720
So you're not just stepping on each other's toes blindly.

919
01:03:34,720 --> 01:03:40,960
The second step is actually being conscious about the commitment you're making to your relationship.

920
01:03:40,960 --> 01:03:51,039
So in a marriage for example people you know I I I talk about co-founder vows and recommmitments and renewals because in a marriage you get married and a lot of

921
01:03:51,039 --> 01:03:57,200
times people build a family and then they think oh the relationship will just continue because we're around each other all the time.

922
01:03:57,200 --> 01:03:59,920
We're doing this thing together.

923
01:03:59,920 --> 01:04:09,039
But just like couples need a date night co-founders need time and space to connect with each other to come together and say how's this working for you?

924
01:04:09,039 --> 01:04:12,160
Are we still aligned on our vision and our strategy?

925
01:04:12,160 --> 01:04:13,920
How are we working together?

926
01:04:13,920 --> 01:04:15,920
What am I doing that's pissing you off?

927
01:04:15,920 --> 01:04:20,079
What are the things that have gone unsaid and that we need to talk about?

928
01:04:20,079 --> 01:04:27,200
But if you're just in the hustle and bustle of running and scaling your startup, you don't make time for that conversation.

929
01:04:27,200 --> 01:04:32,880
So, I think it's incredibly important for co-founders to make space for their relationship.

930
01:04:32,880 --> 01:04:37,920
Whether that's a dinner every other week, whether that's going out to lunch regularly,

931
01:04:37,920 --> 01:04:45,280
whether that's um just touching base business-wise, but having an in-person quarterly check-in,

932
01:04:45,280 --> 01:04:49,839
that space is critical for the health of a co-founder relationship.

933
01:04:49,839 --> 01:04:52,799
>> On that second piece, the vows idea is such a good idea.

934
01:04:52,799 --> 01:04:54,160
Is that something you actually recommend?

935
01:04:54,160 --> 01:04:56,000
Like here's what I vow to do.

936
01:04:56,000 --> 01:04:57,280
>> Yeah, here's what I commit to do.

937
01:04:57,280 --> 01:05:06,799
So, I have um recently I actually wrote an article with First Round and we created a document to help co-founders think about what to integrate into their check-in.

938
01:05:06,799 --> 01:05:14,079
So, we put out weekly check-in, monthly check-in, and annual and just questions to sit down and ask each other.

939
01:05:14,079 --> 01:05:17,920
Active listening skills will come in handy in those conversations.

940
01:05:17,920 --> 01:05:28,480
But it's about taking space out of hustling and running the business to think about the business from a kind of rather I I like to say instead of being

941
01:05:28,480 --> 01:05:34,079
on the dance floor, you need time on the balcony to look down at what's happening.

942
01:05:34,079 --> 01:05:35,200
How are we doing?

943
01:05:35,200 --> 01:05:37,599
Is this still working for both of us?

944
01:05:37,599 --> 01:05:41,200
And the vows are really about how are we going to be together?

945
01:05:41,200 --> 01:05:42,079
How are we going to show up?

946
01:05:42,079 --> 01:05:43,599
Like what's our culture that we're creating?

947
01:05:43,599 --> 01:05:48,400
Even if you don't want to go through a whole culture exercise early on in building your company,

948
01:05:48,400 --> 01:05:51,920
you should have some sense of how you want to show up for each other.

949
01:05:51,920 --> 01:05:55,200
How are we going to make decisions?

950
01:05:55,200 --> 01:05:57,200
How are we going to deal with conflict?

951
01:05:57,200 --> 01:06:03,039
These are things you can go to in go into intentionally and design with your co-founder.

952
01:06:03,039 --> 01:06:03,359
>> Awesome.

953
01:06:03,359 --> 01:06:05,440
We're going to link to that post.

954
01:06:05,440 --> 01:06:12,319
The first step uh anagram sounds like that's what you recommend and this is basically a personality profile that uh a lot of people love.

955
01:06:12,319 --> 01:06:13,520
I really like the anagram.

956
01:06:13,520 --> 01:06:17,680
I think you can also simply tell each other here are my strengths.

957
01:06:17,680 --> 01:06:21,280
Here's what I see as my weaknesses and what do you think?

958
01:06:21,280 --> 01:06:22,160
Give me some feedback.

959
01:06:22,160 --> 01:06:22,960
Do you agree?

960
01:06:22,960 --> 01:06:26,000
And you can do that with each other without any personality assessment.

961
01:06:26,000 --> 01:06:36,559
If you want to just be scrappy and have an open connected conversation about the you could even say what are the gifts I bring and the weaknesses I have

962
01:06:36,559 --> 01:06:38,480
and how will I cover those?

963
01:06:38,480 --> 01:06:39,680
How will I lean into my gifts?

964
01:06:39,680 --> 01:06:40,880
How will I cover my weaknesses?

965
01:06:40,880 --> 01:06:50,960
and how will you and then I think it's worthwhile having a conversation about what are the gaps neither of us cover that we're likely going to need as we build this business.

966
01:06:50,960 --> 01:06:56,160
What do you recommend people do when they are just like our relationship isn't working grades?

967
01:06:56,160 --> 01:06:57,440
Like there's a lot of tension.

968
01:06:57,440 --> 01:07:03,599
All this advice we've been talk talking about is like at the beginning here's things you can do to set things up for success.

969
01:07:03,599 --> 01:07:05,920
Understand what you're good at, what you're bringing to the table.

970
01:07:05,920 --> 01:07:07,920
Consciously commit to here's what I'm going to do.

971
01:07:07,920 --> 01:07:08,799
Here's what you're going to do.

972
01:07:08,799 --> 01:07:10,960
Have these dinners or lunches.

973
01:07:10,960 --> 01:07:16,480
I love this metaphor of going out on the balcony and just reflecting on how is it how it's going.

974
01:07:16,480 --> 01:07:18,400
So that's all really great.

975
01:07:18,400 --> 01:07:24,400
What if you're just already in it and just like this is really annoying and I don't like this person that much or so much tension constantly.

976
01:07:24,400 --> 01:07:26,880
What what are a couple things they can do this week, next week?

977
01:07:26,880 --> 01:07:36,400
>> Co-founders typically come to me either in this early phase where they're they want to intentionally build something great and they want to set it up for success.

978
01:07:36,400 --> 01:07:40,960
More often co-founders come when they're really frustrated with one another.

979
01:07:40,960 --> 01:07:43,440
They feel the tension is palpable.

980
01:07:43,440 --> 01:07:48,400
They can't stand it anymore, but they're still really deeply committed to the business.

981
01:07:48,400 --> 01:07:50,640
So, they don't see an out.

982
01:07:50,640 --> 01:07:54,720
And they knew that at some point they really loved this co-founder.

983
01:07:54,720 --> 01:07:57,280
So, they see a possibility of recovering.

984
01:07:57,280 --> 01:08:00,000
And that's why they want to go get a coach.

985
01:08:00,000 --> 01:08:07,520
I'm going to give you an example of uh this PR duo running a fierce business, scaling really fast.

986
01:08:07,520 --> 01:08:12,960
And at one point when they started, you had the visionary who was great at selling business.

987
01:08:12,960 --> 01:08:17,759
Um they were both incredible with PR and the partner was incredible operationally.

988
01:08:17,759 --> 01:08:28,480
So as the business scaled, one took on a lot more business development and the other took on all the internal things but was exhausted by all this people management and all of

989
01:08:28,480 --> 01:08:35,520
the um elements of kind of running a scaled team that she didn't expect to have to do.

990
01:08:35,520 --> 01:08:40,319
And when they came, I think both of them weren't sure, can we figure this out?

991
01:08:40,319 --> 01:08:41,759
Do we want to just sell this thing?

992
01:08:41,759 --> 01:08:43,839
Do we want to keep going?

993
01:08:43,839 --> 01:08:47,679
And I think someone said, "End it or send it?"

994
01:08:47,679 --> 01:08:50,000
Was what one co-founder said to me.

995
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:54,159
You know, they're coming at this this this decision point.

996
01:08:54,159 --> 01:09:00,000
And what I saw them do is one, they named current state really well.

997
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:02,159
They were both able to share.

998
01:09:02,159 --> 01:09:04,239
We we did use a 360.

999
01:09:04,239 --> 01:09:13,199
So they got feedback from their teams and then shared it with one another, but they were able to be open and vulnerable in what was working and what wasn't working.

1000
01:09:13,199 --> 01:09:16,080
Not immediately, but over time.

1001
01:09:16,080 --> 01:09:25,520
And they realized they used to love being partners in this work, but as they began to lead different teams,

1002
01:09:25,520 --> 01:09:27,279
they grew very distant from one another.

1003
01:09:27,279 --> 01:09:38,319
They were living on opposite sides of the country and actually just coming together and realizing what each other was missing and how lonely it is to lead this scaling company without each other's

1004
01:09:38,319 --> 01:09:48,400
support and how they actually needed the counterbalance to their strengths and didn't have it was a important start to their healing.

1005
01:09:48,400 --> 01:09:57,920
And over our coaching, they turned back towards each other and they created more of a rhythm of how they would get together without me involved.

1006
01:09:57,920 --> 01:10:04,239
And they they ended coaching after our arc feeling renewed and really recommitted.

1007
01:10:04,239 --> 01:10:08,000
They made some changes on their leadership team to fill their gaps.

1008
01:10:08,000 --> 01:10:17,760
They also started, I think, meeting once a week virtually and they started a cadence of getting together in person quarterly.

1009
01:10:17,760 --> 01:10:22,159
And I don't mean to say that just that time means you're going to heal.

1010
01:10:22,159 --> 01:10:25,360
Sometimes coming together and really grappling.

1011
01:10:25,360 --> 01:10:27,520
I had one last week where we all came together.

1012
01:10:27,520 --> 01:10:33,520
We had a great full day in-person discussion about how they were making this co-founder duo,

1013
01:10:33,520 --> 01:10:36,640
how they were making decisions.

1014
01:10:36,640 --> 01:10:46,880
And after that conversation, it was really clear that that one of the co-founders was unhappy and and didn't appreciate the other one and was not

1015
01:10:46,880 --> 01:10:53,120
going to change and realized he was a big part of the problem and I think is going to leave the business.

1016
01:10:53,120 --> 01:10:56,640
But that's still success because it's clarity.

1017
01:10:56,640 --> 01:11:03,520
You're not muddling in the dark, frustrated, unconscious about the interpersonal dynamics you're in.

1018
01:11:03,520 --> 01:11:15,280
You're making a choice based on your strengths and what the business needs and this relationship dynamic that you're in to either be in it or to lovingly step out

1019
01:11:15,280 --> 01:11:15,840
of it.

1020
01:11:15,840 --> 01:11:18,400
>> I love how similar this is to just a marriage.

1021
01:11:18,400 --> 01:11:21,440
All the stuff you're like this is the same sort of thing you do.

1022
01:11:21,440 --> 01:11:21,840
>> Totally.

1023
01:11:21,840 --> 01:11:24,640
I mean a marriage you're building a life with a partner.

1024
01:11:24,640 --> 01:11:29,840
So the only difference is a marriage is rooted in sexual attraction and love.

1025
01:11:29,840 --> 01:11:33,440
And that's not the case always in the co-founder dynamic.

1026
01:11:33,440 --> 01:11:37,520
But I have I have worked with couples who are also co-founders.

1027
01:11:37,520 --> 01:11:41,440
But there should be some element of love for your co-founder.

1028
01:11:41,440 --> 01:11:48,960
In fact, I think that when you work closely with colleagues and you really are able to see their gifts and enable them,

1029
01:11:48,960 --> 01:11:51,840
you can't help but love them.

1030
01:11:51,840 --> 01:11:54,000
>> That's a big statement.

1031
01:11:54,000 --> 01:11:56,800
The other takeaway here is that just get coaching.

1032
01:11:56,800 --> 01:11:59,199
It feels like that's the solution if things are just not working great.

1033
01:11:59,199 --> 01:12:01,440
like there's only so far you can get just talking.

1034
01:12:01,440 --> 01:12:12,239
>> It it takes an evolved facilitator like one of the co-founders being able to hold space for both their frustration and their empathy

1035
01:12:12,239 --> 01:12:14,719
in a dynamic that is challenging.

1036
01:12:14,719 --> 01:12:17,840
So outside support is useful.

1037
01:12:17,840 --> 01:12:19,840
Sometimes it's actually a team member.

1038
01:12:19,840 --> 01:12:21,520
It's an HR leader.

1039
01:12:21,520 --> 01:12:24,480
It's the GC who happens to have great people skills.

1040
01:12:24,480 --> 01:12:30,800
You don't always need a coach, but you need space to be vulnerable, open, and curious.

1041
01:12:30,800 --> 01:12:33,360
So, if you can create that on your own, that's great.

1042
01:12:33,360 --> 01:12:35,280
I think it's definitely possible.

1043
01:12:35,280 --> 01:12:44,000
>> Outside of the co-founder relationship, do you have any just tactical tips for people to improve their interpersonal interpersonal skills with just team members,

1044
01:12:44,000 --> 01:12:48,000
anyone they work with, just people that may struggle like, man, I have a hard time with this person.

1045
01:12:48,000 --> 01:12:50,159
I just have a hard time with a lot of people.

1046
01:12:50,159 --> 01:12:56,960
First of all, people when they want to have a conflict or they want to engage in something that's not working,

1047
01:12:56,960 --> 01:13:00,960
they come in armored and ready to prove their point.

1048
01:13:00,960 --> 01:13:01,679
It's natural.

1049
01:13:01,679 --> 01:13:05,920
You've been thinking about this, proverating over whether you should mention it.

1050
01:13:05,920 --> 01:13:16,640
You finally get to the point of engaging and often there's a misguided view that the goal is to convince the other person that what they're doing is wrong.

1051
01:13:16,640 --> 01:13:22,560
Actually, the goal of any conflict is to create mutual understanding.

1052
01:13:22,560 --> 01:13:30,640
So, when I go in to have a conversation with, let's say, my husband who's not doing his share of the parenting,

1053
01:13:30,640 --> 01:13:37,520
my goal is to help him understand what I'm struggling with so that he can empathize,

1054
01:13:37,520 --> 01:13:44,320
see clearly what's happening, and perhaps meet my needs in some way.

1055
01:13:44,320 --> 01:13:54,159
But it's not for me to prove to him how little he's doing in the house because he might have a totally different story about what's happening.

1056
01:13:54,159 --> 01:14:00,159
So I'm going to give you a framework that I like that many of my clients use.

1057
01:14:00,159 --> 01:14:06,159
It's from Marshall Rosenberg's non-violent communication has a book and a framework.

1058
01:14:06,159 --> 01:14:08,239
So it's four steps.

1059
01:14:08,239 --> 01:14:11,440
The first step is observations.

1060
01:14:11,440 --> 01:14:16,960
So my job is to note what is happening factually.

1061
01:14:16,960 --> 01:14:26,400
For example, I noticed that in the last three sprint planning meetings, you didn't show me what you were you didn't invite me to those conversations or

1062
01:14:26,400 --> 01:14:29,040
share with me the road map.

1063
01:14:29,040 --> 01:14:30,080
That's an observation.

1064
01:14:30,080 --> 01:14:30,719
It's a fact.

1065
01:14:30,719 --> 01:14:34,640
I could take a picture of it and no one would argue with it.

1066
01:14:34,640 --> 01:14:37,040
The next step is feelings.

1067
01:14:37,040 --> 01:14:40,239
So I'm going to express my feelings without blame.

1068
01:14:40,239 --> 01:14:45,520
So, I felt anxious not knowing what was on the road map for the week.

1069
01:14:45,520 --> 01:14:51,280
I felt confused about whether that meeting happened or not because I wasn't included.

1070
01:14:51,280 --> 01:14:58,880
So, this is me sharing my feelings so the other party can empathize and understand what I'm going through without being defensive.

1071
01:14:58,880 --> 01:15:01,360
The third step is needs.

1072
01:15:01,360 --> 01:15:04,560
What are my universal human needs related to this topic?

1073
01:15:04,560 --> 01:15:06,080
We all have needs.

1074
01:15:06,080 --> 01:15:11,920
This is not requiring anything of the other person just helping them understand my needs that are not met.

1075
01:15:11,920 --> 01:15:13,840
So I have a need for clarity.

1076
01:15:13,840 --> 01:15:16,080
I have a need for collaboration.

1077
01:15:16,080 --> 01:15:18,640
I have a need for connection.

1078
01:15:18,640 --> 01:15:20,239
Whatever that is.

